ace in the Eastside of Portland. If you are embarking on a<a title=\"The Current Tenants at Zoomtopia\" href=\"http://zoomtopia.com/community/\">creative enterprise</a>, then this could be your chance to <a title=\"Lease-to-Own Philosophy for arts\" href=\"http://zoomtopia.com/about/\">own your studio</a>.\r\n\r\n<em>Zoomtopia has one remaining studio space to </em><a title=\"Leasing Info\" href=\"http://zoomtopia.com/leasing/\"><em>lease,</em></a> studio #7, with 1000 square feet for light industrial uses. The remainder of our 10,000 square foot building has been leased, and the tenants include:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>three dance companies</li>\r\n	<li>a jeweler</li>\r\n	<li>an arts quarterly and literary festival</li>\r\n	<li>a glass blowing studio</li>\r\n	<li>a photography and multi-media design studio.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWe have 2000 square feet of common space that is being used for gallery space, lectures and book signings, presentations, and small events.\r\n\r\n<strong>This is your chance to join this bustling building, and be a part of the creative community blossoming in the </strong><a href=\"http://www.firstfridayart.com/\"><strong>central eastside arts district</strong></a><strong>.</strong> We are looking forward to the new <a title=\"streetcar plans for eastside on wikipedia\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portland_Streetcar#Eastside_.28under_construction.29\">Street Car line coming in 2012</a>, and the opportunity to collectively own the building around that same time. We are building a strong, cooperative fellowship of artists, designers, performers, makers and doers, and <strong>we want you to join us.</strong>','Lease The Last Remaining Studio or Rehearsal Space at Zoomtopia!',0,'','inherit','open','open','','326-revision-6','','','2010-03-13 15:05:04','2010-03-13 22:05:04','',326,'http://zoomtopia.com/326-revision-6/',0,'revision','',0),(191,1,'2009-04-22 22:43:16','2009-04-23 05:43:16','','Events',0,'','inherit','open','open','','45-revision-2','','','2009-04-22 22:43:16','2009-04-23 05:43:16','',45,'http://zoomtopia.com/45-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(192,1,'2010-01-14 13:34:26','2010-01-14 20:34:26','','Events',0,'','inherit','open','open','','45-revision-3','','','2010-01-14 13:34:26','2010-01-14 20:34:26','',45,'http://zoomtopia.com/45-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(351,1,'2010-07-19 15:02:03','2010-07-19 22:02:03','The creative community that makes up Zoomtopia includes visual artists, web designers, digital photographers, community organizers and mental health practitioners. Here are the people that make up Zoomtopia so far:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://carolezoom.com\">CaroleZoom</a>, developer, artist, activist\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://gabesimagination.com\">Gabe\'s Imagination</a>, design\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://aaronrogosin.com/\">Aaron Rogosin</a>, photography\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.rubberteeth.com/\">tEEth</a>, dance\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://zoomtopia.com/wobbly\">Wobbly</a>, dance\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://moltenimagination.com\">Molten Imagination</a>, glass\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Natya Leela Dance Web Site\" href=\"http://www.natyaleela.com\" target=\"_blank\">Natya Leela Academy</a>, dance\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.wordstockfestival.com\">Wordstock</a>, Portland\'s Book & Literary Festival\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.orlo.org/\">Orlo</a>, publisher of The Bear Deluxe Magazine\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://plunderama.com/\">Plunderama</a>, Unique, Personalized Gifts\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 13.3333px;\">Zoomtopia is located in the Central Eastside Industrial District, which is a vibrant and growing neighborhood. Neighbors include the Grand Central Bowl, Green Dragon Brewery and Oregon Ballet Theatre.</span>\r\n\r\nZoomtopia is also in the heart of Distillery Row, a strip 16 blocks long and five blocks wide, where five independent distilleries (housing seven spirits companies) produce over twenty unique liquors.','Community',0,'','inherit','open','open','','11-revision-v1','','','2010-07-19 15:02:03','2010-07-19 22:02:03','',11,'http://zoomtopia.com/11-revision-20/',0,'revision','',0),(195,1,'2010-01-14 18:17:33','2010-01-15 01:17:33','Join us at Zoomtopia for Jerry McGill\'s reading of \"Dear Marcus: Speaking to the Man Who Shot Me\" on Friday, February 5th at 6pm at  810 SE Belmont. Jerry will read from his memoir and sign books. The event is free and all ages. Softcover and hardcover books available for purchase. \r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://zoomtopia.com/jerry-mcgill-book-signing/jerry-mcgill-flyer-3-pub/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-302\"><img src=\"http://zoomtopia.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/Jerry-McGill-copy-300x265.jpg\" alt=\"Jerry McGill reads from Dear Marcus\" title=\"Jerry McGill Flyer (3).pub\" width=\"300\" height=\"265\" class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-302\" /></a>\r\n\"As a boy, Jerome moves from Brooklyn to the Lower East Side in Manhattan, and everything seems grand.\r\n\r\nThere is more light and more excitement in this new place. And even though times are tough for a family led by a single mother, Jerome sees a promising future for himself. By the young age of twelve, hes already excelling as an athlete and performer.\r\n\r\nBut everything swiftly changes one night for Jerome. Walking home from a party with a friend, hes shot in the back. Shortly after, he learns hell be paralyzed for life.\r\n\r\nJerome never meets his attacker, and the authorities never catch the person. News of a black adolescent getting shot in Manhattan doesnt even rate a paragraph in the local paper. With only his close circle of friends, family and caregivers, Jerome is left looking for answers.\r\n\r\nRather than settle into a world of depression and anger, however, Jerome goes on to live a fulfilling and rewarding life. In this touching memoir, he confronts not only the demons he knows, but the one that remains mysterious, the one he reaches out to in Dear Marcus.\"','Jerry McGill Book Signing 2/5 at 6pm',0,'','publish','open','open','','jerry-mcgill-book-signing','','','2010-02-17 15:05:55','2010-02-17 22:05:55','',0,'http://zoomtopia.com/?p=195',0,'post','',1),(196,1,'2010-01-14 18:17:11','2010-01-15 01:17:11','','Jerry McGill Book Signing',0,'','inherit','open','open','','195-revision','','','2010-01-14 18:17:11','2010-01-15 01:17:11','',195,'http://zoomtopia.com/195-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(197,1,'2010-01-14 18:17:18','2010-01-15 01:17:18','','Jerry McGill Book Signing',0,'','inherit','open','open','','195-revision-2','','','2010-01-14 18:17:18','2010-01-15 01:17:18','',195,'http://zoomtopia.com/195-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(198,1,'2010-01-14 18:17:33','2010-01-15 01:17:33','','Jerry McGill Book Signing',0,'','inherit','open','open','','195-revision-3','','','2010-01-14 18:17:33','2010-01-15 01:17:33','',195,'http://zoomtopia.com/195-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(199,1,'2009-12-19 23:38:50','2009-12-20 06:38:50','Wobbly is a collaboration of partners Erik Ferguson and Yulia Arakelyan. Part visual art, part dance Wobbly Studio represents a sanctuary for exploration occasionally culminating in small public performances and workshops whose content is informed by Butoh, Contact Improvisation, painting, dance, film and more. Wobbly is committed to promoting equal access in the arts, particularly in the areas of dance and disability. ','Wobbly',0,'','publish','open','open','','wobbly','','','2010-01-19 23:44:16','2010-01-20 06:44:16','',0,'http://zoomtopia.com/?p=199',0,'post','',0),(200,1,'2010-01-19 23:32:08','2010-01-20 06:32:08','Wobbly is a collaboration of partners Erik Ferguson and Yulia Arakelyan. Part visual art, part dance Wobbly Studio represents a sanctuary for exploration occasionally culminating in small public performances and workshops whose content is informed by Butoh, Contact Improvisation, painting, dance, film and more. Wobbly is committed to promoting equal access in the arts, particularly in the areas of dance and disability. ','Wobbly',0,'','inherit','open','open','','199-revisi